value.value: any structural anomaly of the paired inferior eminence of the mesencephalic tectum that is involved in preliminary visual processing, and control of eye movements
enlargement of the paired inferior eminence of the mesencephalic tectum
any structural anomaly in the structure of any bundle of myelinated nerve fibers following a defined path through the brain and/or spinal cord

any structural anomaly of a thick bundle of nerve fibers comprising a commissural plate connecting the two cerebral hemispheres; it consists of contralateral axon projections that provides communications between the right and left cerebral hemispheres

smaller thick bundle of nerve fibers comprising a commissural plate connecting the two cerebral hemispheres; it consists of contralateral axon projections that provides communications between the right and left cerebral hemispheres

any structural anomaly of the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions)

underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, in the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions)

underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, in of the enlarged anteriolateral part of the brain; consists of the paired cerebral hemispheres and olfactory bulbs, the basal ganglia and the connecting structures
abnormal or arrest of differentiation or patterning of the epithelial cell layer that lines the neural tube and develops into the nervous system and into the neural crest cells

any structural anomaly of the enlarged anteriolateral part of the brain; consists of the paired cerebral hemispheres and olfactory bulbs, the basal ganglia and the connecting structures, and is considered to be the seat of conscious mental processes; it develops from the anterior-most embryological division of the brain that develops from the prosencephalon

any structural anomaly of thin layer of grey matter on the surface of the cerebral hemisphere that develops from the telencephalon and folds into gyri; it is responsible for intellectual faculties and higher mental functions
increased depth of the mantle covering the surface of the cerebral hemispheres
abnormal formation or pattern of the layers of the cerebral cortex
splitting of the layers of the grey cellular mantle covering the surface of the brain
any structural anomaly of the developing superficial cortical layer located just under the pia matter
any structural anomaly of the upper central part of the cerebral hemisphere
any structural anomaly of the area of the parietal lobe that receives general sensation from the body
any structural anomaly of the area of the parietal lobe that integrates tactile and visual stimuli
any structural anomaly of the area of the frontal lobe that is involved in perception based on sensory stimuli
any structural anomaly of the anterior part of the cerebral hemisphere
any structural anomaly of the area of the frontal lobe that contains the cell bodies of the primary motor pathways
any structural anomaly of the area of the frontal lobe that is involved with integration of voluntary movements and with speech
any structural anomaly of the lower lateral part of the cerebral hemisphere

any structural anomaly of one of three major convolutions of the external surface of the temporal lobe of the cerebral hemispheres that is uppermost and borders the lateral (sylvian) fissure, and contains the primary auditory cortex

label.value: abnormal transverse gyrus of Heschl morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the area of the temporal lobe concerned with hearing
any structural anomaly of the posterior part of the cerebral hemisphere
any structural anomaly of the area of the occipital cortex concerned with vision
any structural anomaly of the deep lying structure of the cerebrum involved with memory storage and spatial navigation

definition.value: The synonym abnormal hippocampal formation is a frequently used synonym in the literature for the hippocampus. It is unfortunate that it implies a developmental process. There is also a lack of consensus relating to terms describing the hippocampus and/or the adjacent cerebral cortex with the term hippocampus sometimes referring to the hippocampal formation (or region) and sometimes only to the Ammon gyrus (Ammon's horn). In this ontology, we have used hippocampus to mean the entire formation (region).

value.value: improper differentiation of the hippocampus
missing convoluted brain structure below the cerebral hemispheres; forms part of the limbic system
a retrogressive impairment of function or destruction of the neuronal cells in the hippocampus

any structural anomaly of one of two interlocking gyri of the hippocampus formation that contains granule cells, which project to the pyramidal cells and interneurons of the CA3 region of the ammon gyrus
any structural anomaly of the layers of the laminar structure of the hippocampus
lack of the section of the hippocampus normally situated above the gyrus hippocampi and composed of three layers, the molecular, granular, and polymorphic layers

any structural anomaly of one or both of the two interlocking gyri of the hippocampus formation; a circonvolution of rhinencephalon, the grey substance of which is rich in big pyramidal neuronal cells

any structural anomaly of the almond-shaped body of basal nuclei anterior to the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle of the brain, within the temporal lobe; this area is involved in aggression and fear responses
any structural anomaly of the forebrain region that coordinates neuronal signaling involved in the perception of smell; it receives input from the sensory neurons and outputs to the olfactory cortex

any structural anomaly of the infoldings of blood vessels of the pia mater covered by a thin coat of ependymal cells that form tufted projections into the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain; choroid plexuses secrete cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and act as a filtration system, removing metabolic waste, foreign substances, and excess neurotransmitters from the CSF

overdevelopment or increased size, usually due an increased number of cells located in the infoldings of blood vessels of the pia mater covered by a thin coat of ependymal cells that form tufted projections into the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain
any structural anomaly of the system of four communicating cavities within the brain that are continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord

any structural anomaly of the cavity in each of the cerebral hemispheres derived from the cavity of the embryonic neural tube; they are separated from each other by the septum pellucidum, and each communicates with the third ventricle by the foramen of Monro, through which also the choroid plexuses of the lateral ventricles become continuous with that of the third ventricle

the luminal space of the lateral ventricles is increased in volume or area, usually with an increase in contained fluid, in the cavity in each of the cerebral hemispheres derived from the cavity of the embryonic neural tube; they are separated from each other by the septum pellucidum, and each communicates with the third ventricle by the foramen of Monro, through which also the choroid plexuses of the lateral ventricles become continuous with that of the third ventricle

any structural anomaly of the narrow cleft inferior to the corpus callosum, within the diencephalon, between the paired thalami; its floor is formed by the hypothalamus, its anterior wall by the lamina terminalis, and its roof by ependyma; it communicates with the fourth ventricle by the cerebral aqueduct, and with the lateral ventricles by the interventricular foramina

the luminal space of the third ventricle is increased in volume or area, usually with an increase in contained fluid, in the narrow cleft inferior to the corpus callosum, within the diencephalon, between the paired thalami; its floor is formed by the hypothalamus, its anterior wall by the lamina terminalis, and its roof by ependyma; it communicates with the fourth ventricle by the cerebral aqueduct, and with the lateral ventricles by the interventricular foramina

any structural anomaly of the irregularly shaped cavity in the rhombencephalon, between the medulla oblongata, the pons, and the isthmus in front, and the cerebellum behind; it is continuous with the central canal of the cord below and with the cerebral aqueduct above, and through its lateral and median apertures it communicates with the subarachnoid space

the luminal space of the fourth ventricle is increased in volume or area, usually with an increase in contained fluid, in the irregularly shaped cavity in the rhombencephalon, between the medulla oblongata, the pons, and the isthmus in front, and the cerebellum behind; it is continuous with the central canal of the cord below and with the cerebral aqueduct above, and through its lateral and median apertures it communicates with the subarachnoid space

any structural anomaly of the paired caudal parts of the prosencephalon from which the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus and subthalamus are derived; these regions regulate autonomic, visceral and endocrine function, and process information directed to the cerebral cortex
overdevelopment or increased size, usually due an increased number of cells in the rostral portion of the brain stem
any structural anomaly of the large ovoid mass of paired bodies containing mostly grey matter and forming part of the lateral wall of the third ventricle of the brain
overdevelopment or increased size, usually due an increased number of cells in the thalamus
